{
  format: 1
  name: struct-fields-compared-in-field-name-text-order
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#annex-b", "§B.4", "§D.2", "§5.1", "§5.3", "§A.7", "§D.4"]
  tags: ["ordering"]
  note: '''
    §B.4 struct: "lexicographic fields in canonical field-name order". This is
    fully determined by SPEC.md, NOT ambiguous:
      - §5.1 ("Fields and object members ... their source order has no semantic
        effect") and §5.3 ("Struct members are unordered named fields") forbid
        any dependence on DECLARATION order. Two packages that declare the same
        struct with its fields written in different orders must sort identically,
        so the field comparison order cannot be declaration order.
      - The only name-derived canonical order Liasse defines is text order: §A.7
        canonical JSON "sorts object keys by the Liasse text order" and §D.4
        sorts object member names "by Unicode scalar order".
    Therefore "canonical field-name order" = the struct's field names in text
    order. The names are `a` (U+0061) and `b` (U+0062), so the fields compare in
    the order a, then b — regardless of how they were declared.

    Attack: a comparator that walks struct fields in DECLARATION order. `pt` is
    deliberately declared (b, a) — the reverse of text order — to expose it.
    Rows:
      p1: { b: 1, a: 2 }
      p2: { b: 2, a: 1 }
    Correct (text order, compare `a` first): p2.a = 1 < p1.a = 2, so p2 < p1.
    A declaration-order comparator would compare `b` first (1 < 2) and wrongly
    emit p1, p2. Only `id` is projected, so no canonical struct wire spelling is
    asserted — only the row order the rule determines.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.annexb.struct@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      rows: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        pt: {
          b: "int"
          a: "int"
        }
      }
      $public: {
        by_pt: { $view: ".rows { id, $sort: [pt] }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      rows: {
        p1: { pt: { b: 1, a: 2 } }
        p2: { pt: { b: 2, a: 1 } }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { watch: "public.by_pt", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { id: "p2" }
        { id: "p1" }
      ] } }
  ]
}
